{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:49:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:49:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18272"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18272"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.87,0,0.03,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10986"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79320"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10986"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7450"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27146"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79320"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tibial tuberosity is a feature of the tibia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is it most appropriate description?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A bony prominence on the anterior surface","A depression on the lateral side","A groove on the posterior surface","A notch on the inferior end","A ridge on the medial side"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tibial tuberosity is an important anatomical feature of the tibia, a bone in the lower leg. It plays a crucial role in the musculoskeletal system, particularly in relation to the knee joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct description of the tibial tuberosity is that it is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebony prominence on the anterior surface of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E. It is located just below the knee joint and serves as the attachment site for the patellar ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA groove on the posterior surface of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - This does not describe the tibial tuberosity, which is on the anterior surface\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA depression on the lateral side of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - The tibial tuberosity is not a depression, nor is it located laterally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA ridge on the medial side of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - The tibial tuberosity is not a ridge and is not on the medial side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA notch on the inferior end of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - The tibial tuberosity is not a notch and is located superiorly, near the knee\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tibial tuberosity is a bony prominence on the anterior aspect of the tibia.","It serves as the attachment site for the patellar ligament.","The tibial tuberosity is located just below the knee joint."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18272"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64642"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T09:18:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T09:19:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10986"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79320"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrie